---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = 'Pre-Tax Deductions: How 401(k), HSA & FSA Boost Your Take-Home Pay';
const description =
  'A clear guide to pre-tax payroll deductions: how 401(k), HSA, FSA, and health-insurance premiums lower your taxable income, the difference between pre-tax and post-tax, the FICA nuance, and a worked example of the tax savings.';

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'What is a pre-tax deduction?',
    a: 'A pre-tax deduction is money taken out of your paycheck before income tax is calculated. Because it reduces your taxable income, you pay tax on a smaller amount, which lowers your total tax bill. Common examples are traditional 401(k) contributions, HSA and FSA contributions, and employer health-insurance premiums.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Do 401(k) contributions reduce Social Security and Medicare taxes?',
    a: 'No. Traditional 401(k) and 403(b) contributions are exempt from federal income tax, but they are still subject to Social Security (6.2%) and Medicare (1.45%) FICA taxes. So a 401(k) lowers your income tax but not your FICA — your future Social Security benefit is calculated on the full amount.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is the difference between pre-tax and post-tax deductions?',
    a: 'A pre-tax deduction comes out before income tax is figured, so it shrinks your taxable income. A post-tax (after-tax) deduction comes out after tax has already been calculated, so it does not reduce your taxable income. A Roth 401(k) contribution and wage garnishments are examples of post-tax deductions.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can an HSA save me both income tax and FICA?',
    a: 'It can. When you fund a Health Savings Account through your employer’s cafeteria (Section 125) plan by payroll deduction, the contribution can be exempt from both federal income tax and FICA. That is a stronger tax break than a 401(k), which only avoids income tax.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How much do pre-tax deductions actually save me?',
    a: 'Each pre-tax dollar saves tax at your marginal rate. With federal income tax brackets running from 10% to 37%, a worker in the 22% bracket saves about 22 cents of federal income tax for every pre-tax dollar — plus any state income tax and, for a cafeteria-plan HSA, FICA on top.',
  },
];

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({ '@type': 'Question', name: f.q, acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a } })),
};

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Pre-Tax Deductions: How 401(k), HSA & FSA Boost Your Take-Home Pay',
  description,
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'EasyPayCalc' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'EasyPayCalc', url: 'https://easypaycalc.com' },
  mainEntityOfPage: 'https://easypaycalc.com/guides/pre-tax-deductions-401k-hsa',
};

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
  itemListElement: [
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: 'https://easypaycalc.com' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Guides', item: 'https://easypaycalc.com/guides' },
    { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: 'Pre-Tax Deductions', item: 'https://easypaycalc.com/guides/pre-tax-deductions-401k-hsa' },
  ],
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} schema={[articleSchema, faqSchema, breadcrumbSchema]}>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 py-12">
    <!-- Breadcrumb -->
    <nav class="text-sm text-slate-400" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-teal-700">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-1.5">/</span>
      <a href="/guides" class="hover:text-teal-700">Guides</a>
      <span class="mx-1.5">/</span>
      <span class="text-slate-600">Pre-tax deductions</span>
    </nav>

    <header class="mt-6">
      <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-xs font-semibold text-teal-700 bg-teal-100/80 ring-1 ring-teal-200 rounded-full px-3 py-1">
        <span class="w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500"></span> Updated for 2025
      </span>
      <h1 class="mt-5 text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 text-balance">
        Pre-tax deductions: how 401(k), HSA &amp; FSA boost your take-home pay
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-slate-500 leading-relaxed">
        A few smart choices on your benefits form can shrink your tax bill without shrinking your lifestyle. Here is how
        pre-tax deductions work, which ones cut which taxes, and exactly how much you can save.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-10 text-slate-600 leading-relaxed">
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">What a pre-tax deduction actually does</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Your paycheck doesn’t tax every dollar you earn. A <strong>pre-tax deduction</strong> is money your employer
          pulls out of your gross pay <em>before</em> income tax is calculated. Because the tax is figured on what’s left,
          you’re taxed on a smaller number — and a smaller taxable income means a smaller tax bill.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Think of it as a discount you set up in advance. If you earn $60,000 and route $5,000 into a traditional
          401(k), the IRS treats your taxable wages as $55,000. You never see that $5,000 on your W-2 as taxable income,
          so it’s never taxed at your income-tax rate this year. That’s the entire mechanism behind &ldquo;pre-tax.&rdquo;
          You can watch this play out live in our
          <a href="/" class="text-teal-600 font-medium underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">take-home pay calculator</a> —
          it has a pre-tax deduction input, so you can type in a 401(k) or HSA amount and see net pay change instantly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Pre-tax vs. post-tax: the key difference</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          The distinction that trips people up is <strong>when</strong> the deduction happens relative to the tax
          calculation.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Pre-tax</strong> — taken out before income tax is figured, so it lowers your taxable income. Traditional 401(k), HSA, FSA, and employer health premiums.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Post-tax</strong> — taken out after tax is already calculated, so it does <em>not</em> lower your taxable income. Roth 401(k) contributions, wage garnishments, and most union dues.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Neither is automatically &ldquo;better.&rdquo; A Roth 401(k) is post-tax today but grows tax-free for
          retirement; a traditional 401(k) is pre-tax today but taxed when you withdraw. This guide focuses on the
          pre-tax side, because that’s what raises your take-home pay <em>right now</em>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">The main pre-tax deductions to know</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">Four types cover almost every paycheck:</p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Traditional 401(k) / 403(b)</strong> — retirement contributions that come out of pay before income tax. The 403(b) is the nonprofit and public-school version of the 401(k).</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>HSA (Health Savings Account)</strong> — for people on a qualifying high-deductible health plan. Contributions made through payroll can dodge both income tax and FICA (more on that below).</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>FSA (Flexible Spending Account)</strong> — pre-tax money set aside for medical costs or dependent care. Note the classic &ldquo;use it or lose it&rdquo; rule: unspent funds may be forfeited at year-end.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span><strong>Employer health-insurance premiums</strong> — your share of medical, dental, and vision premiums is usually taken pre-tax through a Section 125 cafeteria plan.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Each of these has an annual cap set by the IRS. Because those limits are adjusted for inflation nearly every
          year, always <strong>check the current IRS limit</strong> before you decide how much to contribute rather than
          relying on last year’s figure.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">The FICA nuance most people miss</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          &ldquo;Pre-tax&rdquo; doesn’t always mean exempt from <em>all</em> taxes. There are really two payroll taxes to
          think about: <strong>federal income tax</strong> and <strong>FICA</strong> (Social Security at 6.2% and
          Medicare at 1.45%). Pre-tax deductions don’t all treat FICA the same way.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2.5">
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span>A <strong>traditional 401(k)</strong> lowers your income tax, but the contribution is <strong>still subject to Social Security and Medicare taxes</strong>. FICA is withheld on the full amount, which is why your 401(k) contributions still count toward your future Social Security benefit.</span></li>
          <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="mt-2 w-1.5 h-1.5 rounded-full bg-teal-500 shrink-0"></span><span>An <strong>HSA funded through an employer cafeteria plan</strong> can be exempt from <strong>both income tax and FICA</strong>. That extra 7.65% of savings is what makes the payroll HSA one of the most tax-efficient deductions available.</span></li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Health-insurance premiums and FSAs run through a cafeteria plan generally get the same both-tax treatment as
          the payroll HSA. The takeaway: a 401(k) saves you income tax only, while cafeteria-plan health accounts can
          save you income tax and FICA.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">A worked example of the tax savings</h2>
        <p class="mt-4">
          Each pre-tax dollar saves tax at your <strong>marginal rate</strong> — the rate on your last dollar of income.
          Federal brackets run from 10% to 37%, so the higher your bracket, the more each pre-tax dollar is worth.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-teal-200 bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-50 to-white p-6">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-slate-900">Example: a worker in the 22% bracket</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm">
            Suppose you contribute <strong>$5,000</strong> to a traditional 401(k) and your marginal federal income-tax
            rate is <strong>22%</strong>. That deduction cuts your taxable income by $5,000, saving roughly
            <strong>$1,100 in federal income tax</strong> (5,000 × 22%). If your state charges, say, a 5% income tax,
            that’s another <strong>$250</strong> saved. FICA still applies to the 401(k), so no savings there.
          </p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-sm">
            Now put <strong>$2,000</strong> into a payroll <strong>HSA</strong> instead. You save the same 22% income tax
            (~$440) <em>plus</em> 7.65% FICA (~$153) — about <strong>$593 total</strong> on $2,000, because the HSA dodges
            both taxes. Dollar for dollar, the cafeteria-plan HSA delivers the bigger break.
          </p>
        </div>
        <p class="mt-4">
          These figures are illustrative — your real savings depend on your bracket, your state, and how your employer’s
          plan is set up. To see the effect on your own paycheck, plug your gross pay and a pre-tax amount into the
          <a href="/" class="text-teal-600 font-medium underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">EasyPayCalc take-home pay calculator</a>
          and compare net pay with and without the deduction.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- FAQ -->
      <section id="faq">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="mt-6 space-y-3">
          {faqs.map((f) => (
            <details class="group rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white px-5 open:shadow-sm transition">
              <summary class="flex justify-between items-center cursor-pointer list-none font-semibold text-slate-800 py-4">
                {f.q}
                <span class="ml-4 shrink-0 grid place-items-center w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-slate-100 text-slate-500 group-open:bg-teal-100 group-open:text-teal-700 group-open:rotate-45 transition">+</span>
              </summary>
              <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed pb-5 -mt-1">{f.a}</p>
            </details>
          ))}
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="rounded-2xl bg-teal-50 border border-teal-100 p-6 text-center">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-slate-900">See your pre-tax deductions in action</h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-slate-600">Enter your gross pay and a 401(k) or HSA amount to watch your take-home pay update instantly.</p>
        <a href="/" class="mt-4 inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-xl bg-teal-600 text-white font-semibold px-5 py-3 hover:bg-teal-700 transition">Open the take-home pay calculator →</a>
      </div>

      <!-- Related guides -->
      <section>
        <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-slate-900">Related guides</h2>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2">
          <li><a href="/guides/how-to-read-your-pay-stub" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-800 underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">How to read your pay stub</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/gross-vs-net-pay" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-800 underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">Gross vs. net pay explained</a></li>
          <li><a href="/guides/what-is-fica" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-800 underline decoration-teal-200 hover:decoration-teal-500">What is FICA?</a></li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <p class="text-xs text-slate-400 leading-relaxed border-t border-slate-100 pt-6">
        Disclaimer: This guide is for educational purposes only and does not constitute tax, legal, or financial advice.
        Contribution limits and tax rules change and individual situations vary. Verify details with the IRS or a
        qualified tax professional before making decisions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
